ce:section.ce:para:
Dry rock samples were submerged in FW (TDS = 241,00 ppm) and vacuumed (at −1 atmosphere) for 3–5 h. Following this, the system was pressurized to 3000 psi for 2–4 h to ensure complete access to all the pores and saturation of the sample. Samples were centrifuged (Ultra Rock Centrifuge, URC-628) at atmospheric condition to displace the formation brine by crude oil. This helped calculate the irreducible or initial water saturation (S
wi
) and the initial oil saturation (S
oi
). Crude oil-saturated samples were then aged at 100 °C to restore the reservoir wettability to its oil-wet state. The aging effect was studied for periods varying between 0 and 42 days. Aging samples for two weeks proved a good compromise between the relevance and efficiency of testing. Thereafter, samples were tested for oil permeability using a typical coreflood setup.
